For our project, controlling for quality will be determined by the fulfillment of our project success criteria. First, the project will be considered successful despite a maximum delay of one week, as well as being 10% over budget. The goal of the project is to provide an opportunity for students to increase their productivity and improve their computer usage. In doing so, taking no shortcuts with regards to planning and scheduling will ensure that we are able to show the students the tools they need to help them acquire new knowledge and techniques. The risk introduced with this choice is that we will hold the workshop at a time that is not convenient for most students. For our project, this time would fall within the vicinity of finals week, a time in which students are most likely unwilling to attend events. In order to mitigate this risk, we have left the option to hold the workshop at a later date, possibly at the start of the new quarter.
	Second, we will create a website that contains all of the information from the workshop for future reference. Controlling for quality here would require that the links redirect students to the correct sources to obtain the software we present. Moreover, the website will also provide links to more tutorials involving the software. This website will be publicly available for students to access at any time. The most prominent risk from this decision is the fact that some number of students may never visit the site post-workshop. In order to mitigate this risk, we will procure participant feedback after the workshop in the form of a short questionnaire. This feedback will serve as a metric that we can use to gauge overall satisfaction and success of the event. We can then determine if students left the workshop feeling that they increased their productivity.

The foremost risk is the lack of interest in the event. Having students come to the event to be exposed to and potentially learn new technologies is the key goal of our project. In addition, there are technical risks in choosing the types of technologies to showcase. Our knowledge and computer skills can be considered to be intermediate to advanced at best, so there remains a chance where a student will have questions we are unable to answer. To realize the projected benefits of the event, we must choose a reasonable amount of content that is both usable and nurtures future interest.
